title: Monsters: A Fan's Dilemma
author: Dederer, Claire
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I tore through this book. And as I always do with these types of books experienced a roller coaster of emotions as I read. I’ve been waiting for a booI tore through this book. And as I always do with these types of books experienced a roller coaster of emotions as I read. I’ve been waiting for a book that explores this conversation for years. This is one that I have with my own friends on a regular basis. We talk about Cosby, and Woody Allen. We debate JK Rowling being cancelled. We question our love of Tarantino. “Can I still watch a Kevin Spacey movie?” “Is it okay for me to binge Braveheart?” “Can I quote Ginsberg?”Increasingly the list gets bigger, the debates get more difficult and nuanced. What will we tolerate? What is left to consume?While Dederer laid out a very researched story for some artists, others came out unscathed - I think this was a personal book for her— and why shouldn’t it be? This is a personal topic. This book was about her artists. The ones she’s asking herself about. My book would have looked somewhat different, but the questions are the same. The struggles are real.Those looking for someone to tell you what to should maybe avoid this. This is a very personal book, written by a memoirist. But if you can read interesting thoughts, think critically about someone else’s work and make connections to your own life when you read something — this one is for you.I’ll still be ruminating on this topic for a long time, but Dederer has given me more fodder to fuel my pondering....more

review: ann patchett writes so beautifully it's transformative. the stories she writes are so deft, they sweep you in and wrap you up and make you feel like yann patchett writes so beautifully it's transformative. the stories she writes are so deft, they sweep you in and wrap you up and make you feel like you're another character alongside the ones you're reading about.i was so devoted to lara, and so engeged in her story. at times i felt like i was swimming in tom lake along side her, at times i felt like i was her daughter -- eager to hear the next part of her tale.i love what patchett does with family stories -- chosen family, natural family. she is deft at writing relationships so realistic they resonate deep within me as a reader. i also adore how she treats locations in her stories as characters themselves -- both tom lake and the orchard are so influential in the story that their traits become necessary to the mood and take on their own personality. this is extremely hard to do, but she is magical at writing this way. this is a beautiful, hopeful, wonderful story...more

Where it faltered was in the execution of the characters and their motivations. The absolute best part about the book was the world building. The amount of time spent describing the food, the setting and the shops or homes was incredible. I felt like I was there eating every bite or feeling every fabric. I wish Aoki had spent more time with that level of detail on the characters. It seemed like everything about their feelings was “told” to me, not shown. Like how many times Katrina repeated things in her head was a bit overt. Her growth as a character wasn’t fully realized enough for me. review: there was not one story in this book (and there are something like 43 stories) that doesnt perfectly exemplify what it's like to be a woman. i mean itthere was not one story in this book (and there are something like 43 stories) that doesnt perfectly exemplify what it's like to be a woman. i mean it. and whether you have kids, or you don't. whether you're young, or you're old. whether you're black, white, or whatever. you will relate.i don't know how Leesa Cross-Smith did it, but gosh if she didn't encapsulate what it means, feels like, smells like....even SOUNDS LIKE, to be a female in the world. the wants, the desires, the satisfactions, the lip gloss. i found myself tearing through this book so quickly, and shaking my head and laughing and aching. i felt as though it was my life, and is my life, and understood every piece of everything i am.i can't say enough good things....more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: give me more books like this!slipping every so delicately between reality and fantasy, this story is that perfect mix of old folk tale and magical reagive me more books like this!slipping every so delicately between reality and fantasy, this story is that perfect mix of old folk tale and magical realism. it has heart and adventure and murder and romance. there are so many layers and textures and depth. and the unfolding of each and every character is beyond compare.i loved this book! The Swann is a perfect setting. it's an old inn/bar that's magic is in it's stories. and when a dead child shows up, and comes back to life -- the true magic begins. where this story really shines is in the nuance. this child belongs to everyone and no one. all stories link back to her. and as the novel delicately unfolds, we get treated to learning each person's tale, background and life. and how they all intertwine with each other -- and with their version of the mysterious child.i hung on every word of this book, i didn't want it to end, but i couldn't imagine how it was going to. i fell in love with every member of the town, and i wanted to tell my story over a pint at the swann. you will too....more

review: so, 2.5. this book sits on the edge of being worse than i wanted it to be and then ended up only slightly better than i thought it was going to after so, 2.5. this book sits on the edge of being worse than i wanted it to be and then ended up only slightly better than i thought it was going to after i was in it... i think this is another one that suffers from "hype" making it seem like it's going to be the best book i've ever read, and so i went into it thinking i was going to be blown away. in reality, this is a just book about an unlikable unhappy white woman. she was a little bit pretentious -- calling everyone except the main characters by their "stereotype" instead of their name (my black colleagues, the twenty-three year old, the Chilean writer). she's a lot whiney -- pining over her would be girlfriend (ish) from years past who i'm not really sure was really a would be girlfriend at all, actually. she's very selfish -- does she ever ask how anyone else is? does she actually care about the kids she teaches, does she care about her own kids or just shove her breast in their face to shut them up? she's terrible with money -- the magic card really pissed me off, honestly.if the book's called want because it leaves you wanting more as a reader, kudos on the name. if it's called want because you want the narrator to stfu. yeh, that too. ...more

review: what i loved about this story was the eerie doom that sat on it and in it and swirled all around it the entire time i was reading it. like i just feltwhat i loved about this story was the eerie doom that sat on it and in it and swirled all around it the entire time i was reading it. like i just felt something bad was going to happen and i was waiting for it to come. ada is one of those narrators that you don't quite understand. she's sad and sweet and lonely and misunderstood, until you start to wonder if you were wrong about her and she's really just disturbed and quite mad. she's the best type of unreliable woman to spend 200 pages with. her relationship with both her father and with samson are fraught with such deep seeded dependency, it's unlikely either one are going to end well. from the start you have to wonder which one is going to win out, becuase you realize early on that she can't exist in a world where both men are attached to her thin string of "life." i loved this little story. the interstitials from each of the "cures" also served well to break up the novel and to give ada more depth. really well done....more

review: **spoiler alert** Too much promise of something that didn't deliver. Too much foreshadowing. Too many sentences that were hinting at something. "If on**spoiler alert** Too much promise of something that didn't deliver. Too much foreshadowing. Too many sentences that were hinting at something. "If only I'd known then..." "I'd know in a few weeks..." "Only later I'd know..." Just say it already.The main characters were all boring annoying girls. Their stories were banal. They wanted to be tragic, they wanted to be magic. They were boring. The description of this story overpromised. In reality, it was an empty story that went no where. No character development. No connection between the multiple plot lines and the characters. The story was meandering and lofty and a bit pretentious. Also, the author spent no time digging into anything that happened in a meaningful way. Why did the mom suddenly become abusive? Was Luke really just a big perv? How did these girls just get away with everything with all these adults around?It seemed like it was written for a teenager who just wanted to believe that life could actually be this way -- dreamy and utterly unbelievable . It's like, maybe I would have liked this in the period of my life when i liked The Craft. Early 90's? But I'm an adult now....more

title: My Dark Vanessa
author: Russell, Kate Elizabeth*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: pros - this book did a wonderfully realistic job of portraying a teenage victim. the ability of a grown man to manipulate a child into believing that pros - this book did a wonderfully realistic job of portraying a teenage victim. the ability of a grown man to manipulate a child into believing that she was special. the harm that she would cause herself and her family if she told. the fear he instilled in her that her life would be ruined and the pain it would bring her if he revealed what was going on. the power that this man had over this child was all encompassing -- from the time she was 15 until the time she was a grown woman. this much was true. and real. and it was horribly and very tragically portrayed.cons - this story could have been told in half the time. maybe less. the repetitive nature of the abuse was unnecessary. the flashbacks to the same scenes between Strane and Vanessa, the same conversations, the same same same. it was exhausting. and it didn't move the story along. i wish the author had more to tell me. i would have signed up for more. more depth. more relationship between mother and daughter. more between her and her therapist. but the way it currently is written there is a lot of the same. and it just gets old. and makes it less impactful where it probably needs to be....more

review: So I read this book this morning. My husband had it lying around so i picked it up and gave it a try. What I liked:- TCM references.- this is an extreSo I read this book this morning. My husband had it lying around so i picked it up and gave it a try. What I liked:- TCM references.- this is an extremely realistic and intense character study of an extremely depressed woman. Some parts are difficult to stomach, especially as you reflect on them after all the cards are on the table. - the ending. I thought this was a good twisty turny finish. Exciting and suspenseful to the last. Why I didn’t like:- why does it always have to be a broken woman?? Why can’t we get more books about men in stories like The Sixth Sense or of Alec Hardy in Broadchurch?- I agree with other s, situations are a bit contrived move the story along. That being said, I don’t think it detracted that much from my enjoyment of the overall story so — whatever. Overall, I don’t expect these types of books to be works of art. They are fun romps. review: i am not an anxious person by nature. legitimately, there are only a hand full of things that give me angst. this book is now added to that list.i lovi am not an anxious person by nature. legitimately, there are only a hand full of things that give me angst. this book is now added to that list.i love when books make me feel something, and Sally Rooney knows how to do that. she's knows how to embody characters so fully and bring them to life. she has her finger on the pulse of humanity. her understanding of the nuance of conversation and relationships is unparalleled. she brings them to life with her writing in a way that's intensely poetic.marianne and connell should not be friends! their relationship is toxic...yet they are drawn to each other and it's so upsetting as a reader to see them continuously spiral down towards destruction with one another. i think, as a reader, you can take this book one of two ways -- as a love story -- or as a story of destruction. i take it as the latter. perhaps because i've seen (and been in) relationships like this, where you keep revisiting the same person at different points in time because there's and invisible passionate magnetic draw to that person, but they are so harmful to both people. anyway, read this book!!! it's such a good ride. and it's a fascinating study of two broken people who desperately need to be freed from the ties that bind. ...more

review: i have conflicted views of this book. while a lot of what orenstein discovered in her interviews and conversations with young women resonated with me i have conflicted views of this book. while a lot of what orenstein discovered in her interviews and conversations with young women resonated with me, there was a lack of diversity and definitely a lack of solution in this book. There were also a lot of generalizations made based on one or two interviews. The thought that Orenstei went into this study with a particular goal in mind is evident, and I'm not sure she thoughtfully investigated all sides. I tend to agree with a lot of what she said (not all), but she offered too much of her own opinion while presenting these women's stories and I think that brought down the credibility of this investigation.Also, while there were a lot of upsetting revelations made by honest and brave young women, but the last few sentences wrapping up "talk to your teens" really doesn't help layout any realistic steps to help fix this major problem. But I will say it's opened my eyes to a long history of misogyny in religion, culture and society. Growing up Catholic and not really being all that religious now, I found especially intriguing the parts about Mary (Jesus' mother) and the unreachable standard she sets for women in Christian religions. Also really fascinating stuff about WW2 and the Nazi's. title: Trainwreck: The Women We Love to Hate, Mock, and Fear... and Why
author: Doyle, Sady
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: do i think society, including and sometimes foremost other women, perpetuates and denigrates the "train wreck" stereotype. yes.do i think society lookdo i think society, including and sometimes foremost other women, perpetuates and denigrates the "train wreck" stereotype. yes.do i think society looks down on women, particularly if they have what are considered "less than female" behaviors (drinking, cursing, promiscuity, dominance, outspokenness, confidence). yes.do i think this is wrong. yes.while this book had some interesting and thought provoking ideas, i think it was a bit heavy handed and sometimes Doyle only gave half the story in order to prove her point. i think the book is worth reading, it's funny and interesting and very much a true discussion on today's societal system that oppresses women in power, or women in need, or women in general. i wish, however, that the facts were more well represented in some of the cases, because the glaring omission of them sometimes made me wonder if the book was too biased in the direction of feminism.one example. when Doyle discusses films about "crazy ex girlfriends" (fatal attraction) vs. "cute ex boyfriends trying to get the girl back" (say anything)...she fails to bring up the many films about crazy ex boyfriends that there are (Fear, Sleeping with the Enemy). that's only one small example where Doyle conveniently only chooses to point out one side of her story.i truly believe and support what this book stands for, and that's why I think she could have done a better job of backing up her claims so that those out there in the world who don't believe it, wouldn't have so much to pick apart....more

He was so one dimensional it was almost comical at times. This was not a "who done it," nor was it a "psychological thriller" or a crime novel It wasn't really mysterious at all. There was no question in my mind who did it from the first few pages. Brundage made that blatantly obvious. What this was was a character driven story, showing the demise of a relationship that probably shouldn't have been one from the start. What made it readable were the side stories that kept me interested...because frankly I didn't care a bit about the Clares....more

review: i was really disappointed in this book...especially based on all the rave s and award buzz around it. the concept, while interesting, wasn't newi was really disappointed in this book...especially based on all the rave s and award buzz around it. the concept, while interesting, wasn't new...and it really did not deliver up to my expectations.i couldn't stand the writing style. the way she wrote sentences felt so pretentious to me..and by the end it was old, trite and really rather boring.the characters were all horrible non-redeeming people. and though i've said it before, you don't have to be likable to be a "nice" character to make a good book...these guys weren't even all that interesting in their awfulness. the concept of writing a story from one person's point of view, then turning the story on it's head (a la gone girl) is a good one...but this story didn't deliver the punches as promised and ended up being just boring and annoying....more

review: I am going to be honest, i had completely unreachable expectations on this novel due to the pure awesomeness of The Sisters Brothers. i'm not sure it I am going to be honest, i had completely unreachable expectations on this novel due to the pure awesomeness of The Sisters Brothers. i'm not sure it lived up to what i was hoping for, but it was good enough to enjoy.deWitt is an extremely gifted and clever writer. i find his writing style really easy to read and thoroughly enjoyable. this story, or fable, i should say, is quite a yarn. telling of Lucy's adventures as the "Undermajordomo" of Castle Von Aux. There are strange going ons in this novel...that get even stranger as the story progresses...and i'm not quite sure i jived with the absolute strangeness of it. i'm also not quite sure i understand how this novel ends. it's a little boring, a little underwhelming. i was surprised that i didn't love this book...but the words are so well written i can't give it a negative .it's cute and fairy tail-ish and just ok....more

review: i was completely torn between loving and hating this book. i went through chapters where i was riveted and engaged...then chapters where i read paragri was completely torn between loving and hating this book. i went through chapters where i was riveted and engaged...then chapters where i read paragraphs in a row without even paying attention as they couldn't hold my interest, and had to go back and reread them just to move along the story.there are some fascinating tidbits of life after and around the awful accident at the Chernobyl Power Plant. but there are also some draining parts that go nowhere and gave me nothing.i would read another by this author...so i guess that says something....more
